body:
This is partial progress toward #426.

This is just the `TextView` primitive with a "state" variable added that controls how far the candy-stripes should march across the screen. 

The state variable is automatically updated on the `TextView`, so one can re-use the `TextView` to create an animation.

Users can specify with or without a bounding box.

The exact location of the text within the bar depends on the `BoundingBox` option picked.

The primitive computes the total region to animate based upon the typesetting engine's output. Thus it is not recommended to "compress" the amount of whitespace allocated to the animation, because it can cause the animation to have artifacts due to whitespace overflow of typesetting.

Below is an example of the animation effect as seen in hosted mode.

![busy_demo](https://github.com/betrusted-io/xous-core/assets/1168375/a6248f3d-c54a-4d7f-8e0c-360120b4c71b)

This is generated with this snippet (with some boilerplate in the beginning to create the black rectangle in the background, which is used for detecting whitespace overflow errors):

```rust
                        let anim_rect = Rectangle::new_coords(10, 10, 240, 30);
                        let mut tv = TextView::new(Gid::new([0, 0, 0, 0]),
                        TextBounds::BoundingBox(anim_rect));
                        tv.clip_rect = Some(clipping_area);
                        tv.style = TEST_STYLE;
                        tv.ellipsis = false;
                        write!(tv, "Test of busy animation").unwrap();
                        tv.insertion = None;
                        tv.draw_border = false;
                        tv.busy_animation_state = Some(0);
                        for _ in 0..4800 {
                            gfx.draw_textview(&mut tv).unwrap(); // &mut tv's busy_animation_state is updated by this call
                            gfx.flush().unwrap();
                            ticktimer.sleep_ms(100).unwrap();
                        }
```

In reality, the animation will not be as smooth if you're doing something in the background, because the animation updates only every time you redraw the text object, and the time between redraws will vary depending on the task at hand (e.g. if you're doing a big TLS download of data from a Matrix server the time between packets can vary quite a bit).

Requesting review by @nworbnhoj to see if this seems like a reasonable starting point for a wait/delay primitive. This still has to be wrapped in layers of UI framework to make it usable, a `TextView` object is still a bit lower-level than say, the `modals` framework.

One general note for "security" is that inverted text is supposed to be only renderable by highly trusted primitives. Of course, to do the candy-stripe effect, we have to XOR portions of the text to create segments of inverted text. There is a half-ass check to XORs with regions wider than the expected width of the candy stripe to make it harder for someone trying to create inverted text to abuse the core primitive. It's hypothesized with variations in localization and local font size preference selections that "nailing" a primitive to have no artifacts is going to be hard. Also, the password boxes use rounded rectangles, while the primitive only works on rectangles with square edges. This is probably too subtle to be a true visual security element but nonetheless it is still a cue of someone abusing the primitive to fake a secure dialog box.
